    col = mix(col, fg.rgb, fg.a);

    fragColor = vec4(col, 1.0);
}

/*
If you have a cube, and you make a square pyramid from each face to the center,
then turn each pyramid inside out, you get a rhombic dodecahedron. This is a very nice
shape; its kind of like a combination of a cube and octahedron, except it isn't
platonic. If you perform this construction in 4D, however, you do get a platonic solid:
the 24-cell! It is also called the octaplex because of its octahedral faces.
It's a surprisingly easy exercise to show that this is indeed a platonic solid.
The fact that it has octahedral faces makes it easy to see that its Schlafi symbol is
{3,4,3}, meaning it is also self-dual! And it tiles 4D space for the same reason the
rhombic dodecahedron tiles 3D space! Thus, it is objectively the best shape.
In addition, it shares vertices with a standard tesseract and orthoplex (4D octahedron),
which makes it easy to render all three with the same code.
*/

